[1
Date: Sat, 28 Nov 1998 21:27:15 -0500
From: Dr. Stack <stack@traknet.com>

Raccoons can have other neurological diseases. I would cross off
toxoplasmosis, antifreeze poisoning, and distemper. I would also go through
the rule out of whether there was a true exposure. As you are aware one can
pet a rabid animal without an exposure. I don't believe there has ever been
an authenticated case of rabies in a human from a racoon.
Before I vaccinated a bunch of kids for rabies I would see what the lab had
to say. You should be able to get a report within 24 to 48 hours. You have
a five day window before you have to start rabies prophylaxsis.
One also has to remember that the vaccine is not innocuous. There have been
many reports of allergic reactions besides the high cost of PEP [post
exposure prophylaxsis given on days 0,3,7,14,21 or 28 for people exposed to
the rabies virus.
--
Bill Stack, DVM
Director of Animal Disease Control
Onondaga County Health Department
Syracuse, N.Y.
[One cannot argue with the need for laboratory confirmation before
initiating vaccination under normal circumstances. - Mod.MHJ
