[2
Date: Mon, 30 Nov 1998 17:41:20 -0500
From: Sarah Lister <Sarah_Lister@agriculture.senate.gov>

I don't mean to diminish the message that wild animals should be avoided,
especially when they act tame. But I also must respond to the comment that
"Any wild raccoon in a public place in daylight is virtually pathognomonic
for a very suspect rabies case". This is the wise default option when a
human exposure has occurred and an animal is not available for testing.
Yet, I've submitted dozens of neurologic raccoons for rabies testing,
without a positive. We certainly have our share of rabid raccoons in
Maryland, but canine distemper (and an ascarid or two) may be the more
common cause of these signs. While a rabies test is pending, it should be
considered a pending test, not a foregone conclusion.
--
Sarah A. Lister, DVM, MPH
AAAS/AVMA Congressional Science Fellow
Senate Agriculture Committee, Democratic Staff
328A Russell Building
Washington, DC 20510
202-224-5929 Fax 202-224-9287
