[3
Date: Mon, 30 Nov 1998 15:34:22 -0500
From: Cummings, Dr. Ian <ICummings@hnne.org>
Just to "tie the ribbon" upon the anecdotal potential rabies exposure I
described. [Rabies, raccoons - USA (Connecticut) 981126012544, involving
two young boys who rescued a sick raccoon from other boys pelting it with
stones.
The animal tested negative in the end. Perhaps ?distemper. At any rate, the
case still illustrates the concerns raised by terrestrial rabies. One has
to wonder how many such near misses occur that we never hear about.
Occasionally when I see that odd neurologic presentation of aseptic
meningitis or perhaps even that nondescript viral illness (clinically) I
wonder if that's how incubating rabies presents.
The CDC human rabies case reports always describe the hapless primary care
or emergency physician who saw the patient in the early stages of the
disease and diagnosed some bland illness only to be horrified later ...
If for no other reason than to stimulate discussion the case was
interesting.
I'm curious as to the 1991 date given for the Northeast corner of the
state. I recall it being only a few years ago (then again, time moves
quickly when having this much fun...).
--
Ian Cummings
Putnam, CT
e-mail: ICummings@hnne.org
